### Description

`ShadowNode._cameraFrameId` is constructed as a `WeakMap`:

```js
// src/nodes/lighting/ShadowNode.js:286 (dev, 2026-07-05; same on r185)
this._cameraFrameId = new WeakMap();
```

…but it is read and written with **bracket notation** in `updateBefore()`:

```js
// src/nodes/lighting/ShadowNode.js:863 / :869 (dev)
if ( this._cameraFrameId[ frame.camera ] === frame.frameId ) { ... }
...
this._cameraFrameId[ frame.camera ] = frame.frameId;
```

Bracket access on a `WeakMap` does not call `get`/`set` — it does a plain property assignment on the WeakMap *object*, with the camera coerced to the string `"[object Object]"`. So **every camera shares one slot per light**, and the intended per-camera dedup ("has this light's shadow map already been updated for this camera this frame") is actually a global per-light dedup:

```js
const wm = new WeakMap();
const camA = {}, camB = {};
wm[ camA ] = 1;
console.log( wm[ camB ] ); // 1 — both cameras hit the same "[object Object]" key
console.log( wm.get( camA ) ); // undefined — the actual WeakMap is never used
```

### Effect

With a single camera per frame (the common case) the behaviour happens to coincide, which is why this goes unnoticed. With **multiple cameras rendering the same shadow-casting light in one frame** (multi-view / split-screen, cube cameras, or any internal multi-camera pass), the dedup skips the shadow update for camera B because camera A already stamped the shared slot this frame — i.e. it deduplicates on "any camera" instead of "this camera". As a side effect the keys also never get garbage-collected with their cameras (they're ordinary string properties, though there is only ever the one).

### Suggested fix

Use the WeakMap API:

```js
if ( this._cameraFrameId.get( frame.camera ) === frame.frameId ) { ... }
...
this._cameraFrameId.set( frame.camera, frame.frameId );
```

