### Description

**NOTE:** While trying to reimplement VR in my project (since I saw r185 now supports WebXR WebGPU) with WebGL fallback, I ran into some issues. I asked **Claude Fable (High)** and it recommended me to report these issues as bugs and made the description/reproduction steps/examples)

Rendering a scene with an `ArrayCamera` (which is what every WebXR session renders with) produces this error the first time a shader referencing the TSL `cameraPosition` node is built:

```
THREE.TSL: TypeError: Cannot destructure property 'camera' of 'undefined' as it is undefined.
```

Three pieces of code interact:

1. In the ArrayCamera branch of `cameraPosition` ([src/nodes/accessors/Camera.js](https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/blob/dev/src/nodes/accessors/Camera.js)), the `cameraPositions` uniform array registers a render-update callback that destructures the frame:

```js
_cameraPositionArray = uniformArray( positions ).setGroup( renderGroup ).setName( 'cameraPositions' ).onRenderUpdate( ( { camera }, self ) => {
    const subCameras = camera.cameras;
    ...
```

2. `Node.onUpdate()` **replaces** the node's `update` method with that callback ([src/nodes/core/Node.js](https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/blob/dev/src/nodes/core/Node.js)):

```js
onUpdate( callback, updateType ) {
    this.updateType = updateType;
    this.update = callback.bind( this );
```

3. `UniformArrayNode.setup()` initializes its buffer by calling `update()` **without a NodeFrame argument** ([src/nodes/accessors/UniformArrayNode.js](https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/blob/dev/src/nodes/accessors/UniformArrayNode.js)):

```js
this.update(); // initialize the buffer values

return super.setup( builder );
```

That frameless call is written for the class's own `update( /*frame*/ )`, which ignores its argument — but after (2) it invokes the callback from (1) with `frame === undefined`, and the `{ camera }` destructuring throws in the middle of the shader build.

**Real-world impact (WebXR):** `renderer.xr.getCamera()` is an ArrayCamera, so any app whose materials are first compiled *during* an XR session hits this on the first XR frame. The examples don't hit it because their shaders are already built by the desktop render before the session starts; apps that render the desktop view through `PostProcessing`/pass-based pipelines (different shader variants) compile their forward-render shaders for the first time inside XR — and there the TypeError aborts `renderer.render()` mid-frame, every frame, with follow-up errors like `TypeError: Invalid value used as weak map key` from half-populated internal caches. Stack excerpt from a real app in VR:

```
TypeError: Cannot destructure property 'camera' of 'undefined' as it is undefined.
    at UniformArrayNode.<anonymous>
    at UniformArrayNode.setup
    at UniformArrayNode.build
    at UniformArrayElementNode.build
    at StackNode.build
    at ShaderCallNodeInternal.build
```

**Suggested fix:** in `UniformArrayNode.setup()`, initialize the buffer via the class implementation instead of the (possibly replaced) instance method:

```js
UniformArrayNode.prototype.update.call( this ); // initialize the buffer values
```

(or make `onUpdate` compose with the original `update`, or guard the `cameraPositions` callback against an undefined frame).

Affects **both backends** of `WebGPURenderer` (WebGPU and `forceWebGL: true`) — verified on r185. The three code paths involved are unchanged on `dev`.

### Reproduction steps

1. Create a `WebGPURenderer` (either backend).
2. Create any material whose node graph references the TSL `cameraPosition` node.
3. Render the scene with an `ArrayCamera` (2 sub-cameras, like WebXR).
4. On the first render (first shader build) the console shows
   `THREE.TSL: TypeError: Cannot destructure property 'camera' of 'undefined' as it is undefined.`
   and the material does not render correctly. No XR device is required.

