### Description

**NOTE:** While implementing occlusion culling after https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/issues/33759 was solved, I ran into new issues. I asked **Claude Fable (High)** and it recommended me to report these issues and made the description/reproduction steps/examples)

In `WebGPUBackend.beginRender()`, the occlusion bookkeeping (`occlusionQueryIndex`,
`occlusionQueryObjects`, `lastOcclusionObject`) is only reset inside
`if ( occlusionQueryCount > 0 )`, and `renderContextData.occlusionQuerySet` is never cleared when
the count is 0.

So when a render context goes from *N > 0* occlusion queries in one frame to *0* in the next
(object hidden, removed, or frustum-culled), the next frame's render pass is created **without**
an `occlusionQuerySet` in its descriptor, but the per-draw code still sees the stale state:

```js
// draw(): renderContextData.occlusionQuerySet is stale from the previous frame
if ( renderContextData.occlusionQuerySet !== undefined ) {

	const lastObject = renderContextData.lastOcclusionObject; // stale: last frame's occlusionTest mesh
	if ( lastObject !== object ) {

		if ( lastObject !== null && lastObject.occlusionTest === true ) {

			renderContextData.currentPass.endOcclusionQuery(); // pass has no occlusionQuerySet → validation error
```

Result: **`No occlusion queries are active`** on EndOcclusionQuery and
**`Invalid CommandBuffer from CommandEncoder renderContext_N`** on `Queue.Submit`, every frame
until an `occlusionTest` object becomes visible again.

Note this requires the stale `lastOcclusionObject` to be an `occlusionTest` object, i.e. the
occlusion-tested mesh must have been the last object drawn in the previous frame — forced with
`renderOrder` in the repro below (in a real scene, render-list sorting hits this arrangement
regularly).

### Reproduction steps

1. Add two meshes: `meshB` plain (drawn first), `meshA` with `occlusionTest = true` (drawn last, via `renderOrder = 1`).
2. Render one frame — works, one occlusion query runs.
3. Set `meshA.visible = false` so the next frame's `occlusionQueryCount` is 0.
4. Render again — the console shows `No occlusion queries are active` on EndOcclusionQuery and an `Invalid CommandBuffer` error on Queue.Submit.

### Code

Demo code
```js
import * as THREE from 'three';

const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera( 70, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 100 );
camera.position.z = 5;

const scene = new THREE.Scene();
const geometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry();

// Plain mesh, drawn first.
const meshB = new THREE.Mesh( geometry, new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial( { color: 0x00ff00 } ) );
meshB.position.x = 1.5;
meshB.renderOrder = 0;
scene.add( meshB );

// Occlusion-tested mesh, drawn LAST so it stays `lastOcclusionObject` after the frame.
const meshA = new THREE.Mesh( geometry, new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial( { color: 0xff0000 } ) );
meshA.position.x = - 1.5;
meshA.occlusionTest = true;
meshA.renderOrder = 1;
scene.add( meshA );

const renderer = new THREE.WebGPURenderer( { antialias: true } );
renderer.setSize( window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight );
document.body.appendChild( renderer.domElement );
await renderer.init();

renderer.render( scene, camera ); // frame 1: one occlusion query — OK

meshA.visible = false; // occlusionQueryCount drops to 0 next frame

renderer.render( scene, camera ); // frame 2: validation errors
```

