### Description

**NOTE:** While implementing occlusion culling after https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/issues/33759 was solved, I ran into new issues. I asked **Claude Fable (High)** and it recommended me to report these issues and made the description/reproduction steps/examples)

`WebGPUBackend` sizes the occlusion query bookkeeping from the render list
(`renderContext.occlusionQueryCount = renderList.occlusionQueryCount`), but
`beginOcclusionQuery()` / `endOcclusionQuery()` are only issued for objects that are actually
drawn. When a custom `renderObjectFunction` skips an object that is on the render list, the
query index can never reach the query count, and three things go wrong:

- `finishRender()` runs `if ( occlusionQueryCount > renderContextData.occlusionQueryIndex ) currentPass.endOcclusionQuery();` with no query active → **`No occlusion queries are active`** validation error, which invalidates the encoder → **`Invalid CommandBuffer from CommandEncoder renderContext_N`** on `Queue.Submit`.
- `renderContextData.occlusionQueryObjects` keeps `undefined` holes at the skipped slots, and the never-begun query resolves to 0, so `resolveOccludedAsync()` executes `occluded.add( undefined )` → **`TypeError: Invalid value used in weak set`** (as an unhandled promise rejection).

This is not exotic usage — core code paths skip listed objects themselves:

- `OutlineNode.updateBefore()` renders its mask/depth passes with a `renderObjectFunction` that only draws the selected objects,
- the shadow pass `renderObjectFunction` skips objects with `castShadow === false`.

So combining `occlusionTest = true` with `outline()` post-processing (or with shadow-mapped
lights and non-shadow-casting occlusion-tested objects) triggers GPU validation errors every
frame.

Note the desync needs the drawn occlusion-tested object's query to be closed by an object
*transition* before the pass ends (i.e. some other object is drawn after it); otherwise the
dangling `endOcclusionQuery()` in `finishRender()` happens to close the still-open query and
only the `TypeError` occurs. The repro below forces this with `renderOrder`.

### Reproduction steps

1. Add three meshes: `meshA` with `occlusionTest = true` (drawn first), `meshB` with `occlusionTest = true` (drawn second), `meshC` plain (drawn last) — order forced via `renderOrder`.
2. Set a custom `renderObjectFunction` that skips `meshB` (this simulates what OutlineNode's mask/depth passes and the shadow pass do internally).
3. Call `renderer.render(scene, camera)`.
4. Devtools console shows, per frame: `No occlusion queries are active` on EndOcclusionQuery, `Invalid CommandBuffer` on Queue.Submit, and `TypeError: Invalid value used in weak set` from `WebGPUBackend.resolveOccludedAsync` (unhandled promise rejection).

### Code

Demo code
```js
import * as THREE from 'three';

// bug 1: TypeError surfaces as an unhandled rejection — make it visible in embedded consoles
window.addEventListener( 'unhandledrejection', e => console.error( 'UNHANDLED REJECTION:', e.reason ) );

const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera( 70, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 100 );
camera.position.z = 5;

const scene = new THREE.Scene();
const geometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry();

// Drawn first, has an occlusion query.
const meshA = new THREE.Mesh( geometry, new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial( { color: 0xff0000 } ) );
meshA.position.x = - 2;
meshA.occlusionTest = true;
meshA.renderOrder = 0;
scene.add( meshA );

// Listed with a query slot, but skipped by the renderObjectFunction below.
const meshB = new THREE.Mesh( geometry, new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial( { color: 0x00ff00 } ) );
meshB.occlusionTest = true;
meshB.renderOrder = 1;
scene.add( meshB );

// Plain mesh drawn after meshA so the object transition closes meshA's query.
const meshC = new THREE.Mesh( geometry, new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial( { color: 0x0000ff } ) );
meshC.position.x = 2;
meshC.renderOrder = 2;
scene.add( meshC );

const renderer = new THREE.WebGPURenderer( { antialias: true } );
renderer.setSize( window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight );
document.body.appendChild( renderer.domElement );
await renderer.init();

// Simulate what OutlineNode's mask/depth passes and the shadow pass do:
// iterate the render list but skip some of the listed objects.
renderer.setRenderObjectFunction( ( object, scene, camera, geometry, material, group, lightsNode, clippingContext ) => {

	if ( object === meshB ) return; // skip a listed object that has occlusionTest = true

	renderer.renderObject( object, scene, camera, geometry, material, group, lightsNode, clippingContext );

} );

renderer.render( scene, camera );
```

