### Description

  When using module-level shared texture nodes (e.g. texture(dummyTexture)) with onObjectUpdate to dynamically switch the texture value per object, the textureData.bindGroups Set grows indefinitely, even when materials are properly disposed.
The root cause is in Bindings._destroyBindings(). When a RenderObject is disposed (via material.dispose()) and groupData.usedTimes reaches 0, for bindings where binding.isSampledTexture === true, the code only calls binding.release() (which sets this._texture = null), but does not remove the bindGroup from textureData.bindGroups Set.
The textureData.bindGroups Set is only cleaned up by Textures._destroyTexture(), which is triggered by texture.dispose(). For module-level shared/dummy textures that are never disposed, this Set accumulates stale bindGroup references indefinitely. Each stale bindGroup holds a strong reference to its NodeSampledTexture bindings, preventing them from being garbage collected.

### Reproduction steps

1. Create a module-level shared texture node: const sharedTex = texture(dummyTexture)
2. Use sharedTex.onObjectUpdate(({ material }) => material.myTexture) to dynamically bind different textures per object
3. Repeatedly create and dispose materials (e.g. terrain tiles in a 3D map engine)
4. The textureData.bindGroups Set grows unbounded — each RenderObject's bindGroup is added but never removed

### Code


  Relevant code (r185.1):
  =======================
```javascript
  Bindings._destroyBindings():
    } else if ( binding.isSampler ) {
        if ( binding.isSampledTexture !== true ) {
            this.backend.destroySampler( binding );
        }
        // BUG: binding._texture is a NodeSampledTexture — its bindGroup should be removed
        // from textureData.bindGroups before calling release()
        binding.release();
    }

  Textures._update():
    texturesTextureData.bindGroups.add( bindGroup );  // Only adds, never removed

  Textures._destroyTexture():
    // Only triggered by texture.dispose(), never by material.dispose()
    if ( textureData.bindGroups ) {
        for ( const bindGroup of textureData.bindGroups ) { ... }
    }
``` 
  Suggested fix:
  =============
  In _destroyBindings(), when binding.isSampledTexture === true, remove the bindGroup from the
  associated textureData.bindGroups Set before calling binding.release():

```javascript
    } else if ( binding.isSampler ) {
        if ( binding.isSampledTexture !== true ) {
            this.backend.destroySampler( binding );
        } else if ( binding._texture ) {
            const texData = this.textures.get( binding._texture );
            if ( texData && texData.bindGroups ) {
                texData.bindGroups.delete( bindGroup );
            }
        }
        binding.release();
    }
``` 


